column89:
I strongly feel that transgender and non-gender-conforming are very different and often mutually exclusive.  Requiring people to choose both or neither left me with no answer that was right.
Also, assuming that everyone works for a company or business leaves out those of us working in higher (or other) education, government, or non-profit organizations.  It's a common (and annoying) mis-labeling.
Was there a question about are you male or female?  I don't remember it, and that's a huge area of under-representation and just plain loneliness for me in tech.   So many times I have "oh, wow, another woman!" experience.

column89: I actually had a hard time answering a lot of these questions. For example, I had to choose a size for the "company" i work for, but I freelance for a variety of organizations, so I don't relate to working for a "company". I had to answer a question about my racial identify, but I don't relate to that either. In Canada we don't tend to categorize people according to race as much as they do in the US, so that may be why. It's not something I think about. Surely in part because I am white, but also because my culture doensn't empahsize this. The class questions were also very difficult to answer - I don't relate to those class boundaries at all. It might have been interesting to add a "I don't relate to this question" option for many of these. Maybe people in the minority groups would be more likely to identify with certain options.

column89: A husband, a father, a follower of Jesus. Actually, in Technology, I'd say that expressing a Christian identity, at least for me, is very hard. There is so much judgmentalism associated with Christianity and anti-Christian perspectives are often still seen as the underdog (though the Biblical worldview is held by a very small minority in almost all English-speaking, developed countries). Or maybe it's that "enlightened" perspectives perceive Christianity as entirely stone age and "stupid"? Certainly Christians, as a group, have done much to incur wrath, ridicule, and disdain. But like any group, especially any large group, it's very complex and diverse. I'd say much of this applies to religion in general within Technology, since the religion of Technology is Naturalism, and any competitor to that is viewed with disdain and suspicion.

Just want to say thanks for doing this survey. Even at my wonderful company, which is comprised of at least half women, and includes several LGBT persons and different religious groups, I look around every week and wonder where my peers of color are, and why they didn't rise like we did, and what I can do to uplift new coders from backgrounds that didn't put their life's difficulty-setting to more or less "easy."
